data.enText: something that you allow or do, or allow sb to have, in order to end an argument or to make a situation less difficult

data.chText: 要想避免罢工，公司将不得不作出一些让步。
data.enText: The firm will be forced to make concessions if it wants to avoid a strike.
to win a concession from sb

data.chText: 她丝毫也不体谅他的年龄，要求他干得像她一样卖力。
data.enText: She made no concession to his age; she expected him to work as hard as she did.
the act of giving sth or allowing sth; the act of conceding

data.chText: 对某些学院升为大学的许可
data.enText: the concession of university status to some colleges

data.chText: 克里承认竞选失败的讲话
data.enText: Kerry's concession speech (= when he admitted that he had lost the election)

data.chText: 减价；（对某类人的）减价票
data.enText: a reduction in an amount of money that has to be paid; a ticket that is sold at a reduced price to a particular group of people

data.chText: 票价为3英镑，学生票减免1英镑。
data.enText: Tickets are £3; there is a £1 concession for students.

data.chText: 成人、优惠、家庭票价分别为2.50英镑、2英镑、5英镑。
（尤指由政府或雇主给予的）特许权，优惠
data.enText: a right or an advantage that is given to a group of people, an organization, etc., especially by a government or an employer

data.chText: 玻利维亚政府批准了在2 200万公顷土地上的伐木特许权。
data.enText: The Bolivian government has granted logging concessions covering 22 million hectares.

data.chText: （在某地的）特许经营权；（有时为大型建筑物或商场中的）销售场地，摊位
data.enText: the right to sell sth in a particular place; the place where you sell it, sometimes an area which is part of a larger building or store

data.chText: 体育场内的汉堡包小吃摊
data.enText: the burger concessions at the stadium

ex.chText: 双方达成妥协以解决他们之间的分歧。
ex.enText: Both sides reached a compromise to settle their differences.

ex.chText: 这两个邻国之间的政治和解已经取得进展。
ex.enText: Progress has been made towards a political compromise between the two neighboring countries.

ex.chText: 在现代婚姻中妥协是必不可少的。
ex.enText: Compromise is inevitable in modern marriage.

synonyms.bx: 指有关各方或人员均作出让步以达成的折中协议，也指妥协的行为。

ex.chText: 我们希望你们能在价格上作些让步。
ex.enText: We hope that you can make some concession on price.

ex.chText: 公司承诺给我们涨工资，这是公司对我们的要求作出的让步。
ex.enText: The company promised to increase our pay, which was its concession to our demands.

synonyms.bx: 指为结束争执、分歧等而对他方作出的退让。

ex.chText: 美满的婚姻在很大程度上取决于互敬互让。
ex.enText: A happy marriage depends largely on give-and-take.

ex.chText: 在任何人际关系中，都得互相忍让。
ex.enText: In any relationship, there has to be some give-and-take.

synonyms.bx: 指为满足彼此的意愿、要求等而互相作出的让步。

tr: a contract granting the right to operate a subsidiary business
example: he got the beer concession at the ball park

tr: the act of conceding or yielding

example: they won all the concessions they asked for

value.def: If you make a concession to someone, you agree to let them do or have something, especially in order to end an argument or conflict.

example.ex: The King made major concessions to end the confrontation with his people.
example.tran: 为了结束与其臣民的冲突，国王作出了很大的让步。

value.tran: (尤指为平息争端或冲突而作出的)让步，妥协

value.def: A concession is a special right or privilege that is given to someone.

example.ex: The government has granted concessions to three private telephone companies.
example.tran: 政府已经向3家私营电话公司授予了特许权。

example.ex: ...tax concessions for mothers who stay at home with their children.
example.tran: 针对在家照顾孩子的母亲的纳税优惠

value.def: A concession is a special price which is lower than the usual price and which is often given to old people, students, and the unemployed.

example.ex: Open daily; admission £1.10 with concessions for children and OAPs.
example.tran: 每天开放;门票1.10英镑，儿童和退休人士可享受票价优惠。

value.tran: (通常指针对老人、学生和失业人员的)优惠价格

value.boxr_value: in AM, use 美国英语用 reduction

value.def: A concession is an arrangement where someone is given the right to sell a product or to run a business, especially in a building belonging to another business.
value.tran: (尤指在别家公司大楼内的)销售权(或经营权)协议

value.boxr_value: in BRIT, usually use 英国英语通常用 franchise
